6.2 FEW-SHOT
Few-shot learning experiments for Omniglot and Mini-Imagenet are presented at Table 3 and Table 4 respectively.
We evaluate our model by performing different q-shot, K-way experiments on both datasets. For every few-shot task T , we sample K random classes from the dataset, and from each class we sample q random samples. An extra sample to classify is chosen from one of that K classes.
Omniglot: The GNN method is providing competitive results while still remaining simpler than other methods. State of the art results are reached in the 5-Way experiments. In the 20-Way 1-shot setting the GNN is providing same results than Munkhdalai & Yu (2017) while still being a more simple apporach. The meta-learning approach from Mishra et al. (2017) is performing better than the GNNs, specially for 20-way although the number of parameters is reduced from 1M (TCML) to 200K (GNN) in the Omniglot architecture.
At Mini-Imagenet table we are also presenting a baseline "Our metric learning + KNN" where no information has been aggregated among nodes, it is a K-Nearest Neighbors applied on top of the pair-wise learnable metric (x(i0), xj(0)) and trained end-to-end. A significant improvement (from 61.4% to 65.5%) can be seen for the 5-shot 5-Way Mini-Imagenet setting when aggregating information among nodes by using the GNN architecture. A variety of embedding functions  are used among the different papers for Mini-Imagenet experiments, in our case we are using a very simple network of 4 layers (Section 6.1.2) which served us to compare between Our GNN and Our metric learning + KNN and it is useful for fast prototyping. More complex embeddings can provide better accuracies, at Mishra et al. (2017) a deep residual network is used as embedding network  increasing the results considerably.
6.3 SEMI-SUPERVISED
Semi-supervised experiments are performed on the 5-way 5-shot setting. Different results are presented when 20% and 40% of the samples are labeled. The labeled samples are balanced among
