Two strategies can be seen at Tables 5 and 6. "GNN - Trained only with labeled" is equivalent to the supervised few-shot setting, for example, in the 5-Way 5-shot 20%-labeled setting, this method is equivalent to the 5-way 1-shot learning setting since it is ignoring the unlabeled samples. "GNN - Semi supervised" is the actual semi-supervised method, for example, in the 5-Way 5-shot 20%labeled setting, the GNN receives as input 1 labeled sample per class and 4 unlabeled samples per class.
Omniglot results are presented at table 5, for this scenario we observe that the accuracy improvement is larger when adding images than when adding labels. The GNN is able to extract information from the input distribution of unlabeled samples such that only using 20% of the labels in a 5-shot environment we get even closer to the 100% supervised results than to the 20% supervised.
In Mini-Imagenet experiments, Table 6, we also notice an improvement when using semi-supervised data although it is not as significant as with Omniglot. The distribution of Mini-Imagenet images is more complex than for the Omniglot dataset. In spite of it the GNN manages to improve by almost 2% in the 20% setting and 1.2% in the 40% setting.

6.4 ACTIVE LEARNING
We performed Active Learning experiments on the 5-Way 5-shot set-up when 20% of the samples are labeled. In this scenario our network will query for the label of one sample from the unlabeled ones. The results are compared with the Random baseline where the network chooses a random sample to be labeled instead of the one that maximally reduces the loss of the classification task T .
Results are shown at Table 7. The results of the GNN-Random criterion are practically the same than the Semi-supervised results for 20%-labeled samples from tables 5 and 6. It means that selecting one random label practically does not improve the accuracy at all. When using the GNN-AL learned criterion, we notice an improvement of almost 1% for Mini-Imagenet, it means that the GNN is managing to correctly choose a more informative sample than a random one. In Omniglot the improvement is smaller since the accuracy is almost saturated and the improving margin is less.

